The mission of the SSP is to cooperatively manage specific, and typically threatened or endangered, species populations such as lowland gorillas.

The size of the wild gorilla’s population is unknown, but the World Wildlife Fund (WWF) believes that the Western lowland gorilla’s numbers have declined by more than 60 per cent over the last 20 to 25 years, leaving them critically endangered.

As well as being threatened by human behaviour such as illegal hunting for their skins and meat and deforestation, female Western lowland gorillas do not produce many offspring.

This is because they do not reach sexual maturity until the age of eight or nine and look after their dependent young for up to five years.

